# TypeScript Standards

## Type Safety Principles

**TypeScript-Specific:**
- Enable `strict: true` in tsconfig.json
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` when type is truly unknown
- Define return types explicitly for public APIs
- Use branded types for IDs to prevent mixing
- Leverage discriminated unions for state machines

## General Type Safety Principles

- Use the strictest type checking available
- Prefer compile-time errors over runtime errors
- Use type inference where it improves readability
- Avoid `any`/`unknown`/dynamic types unless necessary
- Define interfaces/types for all data structures
- Use union types for mutually exclusive states

## Type Safety Checklist

- [ ] All function parameters have types
- [ ] All return values have types
- [ ] No use of `any`/`unknown` without justification
- [ ] External data validated against types
- [ ] Type errors caught at compile/build time

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use interfaces for object shapes
- Use type aliases for unions/intersections
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for extensibility
- Use `const` assertions for literal types
- Use `as const` for immutable data structures
- Leverage utility types (`Partial`, `Pick`, `Omit`, etc.)

## Module System

- Use ES modules or CommonJS consistently
- Prefer named exports over default exports
- Use `export type` for type-only exports
- Avoid `export *` (be explicit about exports)

## Compilation

- Enable declaration maps for debugging
- Use source maps for development
- Compile to appropriate target (ES2020+)
- Enable incremental compilation for faster builds
